# Herdr Reboot Triage

Flagg rebooted. The herdr session came back with 59 panes across 37 workspaces: dead shells with stale labels, reattached pi sessions parked on NEEDS JOEL, a few live claude panes, and janitor STALE flags everywhere with no harvest evidence to act on.

## Finish line

- Every workspace (except the two live ones excluded below) carries a verdict: SHIPPED, ABANDONED, BLOCKED-ON-JOEL, INTERESTING, or ACTIVE — with evidence.
- A triage report exists in this effort dir listing every verdict, plus a continuation prompt with full context for each INTERESTING thread.
- Harvest receipts are written for SHIPPED/ABANDONED panes so herdr-janitor can close them; lying pane labels are corrected.
- Joel can pick any continuation prompt and start a fresh session without archaeology.

Maintained by: the report is a point-in-time artifact; future reboots re-run this playbook, they don't edit this report.

## Vocabulary

- **dead shell** — a pane whose pre-reboot agent process died; the label survives, the context lives only in session transcripts and repo state.
- **verdict** — one of SHIPPED / ABANDONED / BLOCKED-ON-JOEL / INTERESTING / ACTIVE, assigned per workspace with evidence.
- **continuation prompt** — a self-contained prompt (objective, state with receipts, session paths, next steps, gotchas) that lets a fresh session resume a thread.
- **harvest receipt** — the steering statement janitor needs: output reviewed, outcome (committed / rejected / no changes needed), pane may close.

## Notes

- Skills: `herdr-orchestration` (fan-out + janitor cooperation), `grill-master`, `session-search` (transcript locations).
- Execution authorized (Joel, 2026-07-20): investigation workers, report writing, pane renames, harvest receipts. Pane closes go through janitor, not raw closes of panes this session didn't create.
- Excluded from triage: w1R (resilience charter, claude actively working) and w1T (this steering session).
- Live claude panes (wB:p5, wY:p1, w1P:p1, w1S:p1) are read-only: `herdr pane read` only, never send keys, never close.

